309
33:14.190 --> 33:19.915
So here's what it looks
like when N is equal to one, which isn't a very interesting case.

310
33:19.915 --> 33:28.302
Here it is for N is equal to two, and you'll notice what we get in this case is a Hadamard operation.

311
33:28.302 --> 33:31.560
Here's the quantum Fourier
transform for N equals three.

312
33:31.560 --> 33:36.122
For N equals four, which
we've already seen.

313
33:36.122 --> 33:41.220
And for one last example, here it is when N is equal to eight.

314
33:41.220 --> 33:47.700
Just like we had before
for the N equals four case, These are the matrices that we associate with the discrete Fourier transform

315
33:47.700 --> 33:56.340
for each of the dimensions. But we call it the
quantum Fourier transform when we want to think about
it as a quantum operation.

316
33:56.340 --> 34:04.110
Sometimes by the way, the leading factor of one over the square root of N is not included when we think about the discrete Fourier
transform as a matrix,

317
34:04.110 --> 34:09.540
but we need that factor here to make sure that we get a unitary matrix.

318
34:09.540 --> 34:14.250
There's also sometimes a minus sign in each of the exponents, but not always.

319
34:14.250 --> 34:20.490
It's basically just a personal preference that doesn't change the fundamental
nature of the transform.

320
34:20.490 --> 34:29.790
But in any case, we'll define the quantum Fourier transform as it's written here on the screen.

321
34:29.790 --> 34:35.610
There's a very useful shorthand
notation that's common and we'll make use of it
